       <br><b><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#4681BD" weight="bold">.:Farewell:.</font></b><br>
<small><font size="1" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#0F7B66">Thursday, April 17 2003</font></small><br><br>

<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><font color="#FFFFFF">Those of us fortunate enough to have competed in front of tens, hundreds or possibly thousands of supporting fans know there is nothing quite like it. There will never be anything like a last second game winning shot, nor the adrenaline of a bitter playoff battle. And while the game of basketball exists in pick-up games on private courts, it will never come close to playing against the best there are, amongst your most ardent supporters and greatest detractors. Michael Jordan's itch and eventualy return to the NBA was understandable if not predictable. Not one of us, who loves the game of basketball at any level would begrudge the chance to have a single shot or just one more chance at playing in the NBA. Why should he?</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
People asked last year "why come back?", "Why jeopardize an ending that at the very least was storybook and a career, legendary?" Today during a meaningless lopsided defeat, as fans chanted "We want Mike, We Want Mike!" and as irrelevant free throws drew ovations we understood why. </P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
We are left in the wake of his final game with uncounted memories, glimpses of the outstanding physical feats humans are capable of. If the most outstanding of such framed images came with Michael in a Bulls uniform, then these last two seasons sprinkled amongst our collection the greatness of human will. We remember his sick game against the jazz, the endless elevation of the game winning shot against the Cavaliers and the confused shrug against Portland. Forever replayed in our minds and in video will be the acrobatic layup against the Lakers and the double clutch foul line dunk at All-Star Weekend. Now we will remember a 39 year old's two handed block against his former team, and how even at forty, forty points did not seem a daunting task.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Last time it ended with a game winning shot and an NBA Championship. Last time we hoped it would not be the end. Last time with arm extended in an unforgettable pose Michael Jordan seemingly said thank you and goodbye to us.  </P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
This time there were no finals, no playoffs and only the 82 regular season games. This time we knew exactly when the era would ultimately end. This time around there was no glory or championship and yet this time it ended in the way it should have. This time, the league, the players and we the fans finally got to say thank you, and farewell to him.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
</p></font></font>
<small><font size="1" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#0F7B66">
