</P></font></small><br>

<br><b><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#4681BD" weight="bold">.:Protests and Freedom of Speech:.</font></b><br>
<small><font size="1" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#0F7B66">Wednesday, April 02 2003</font></small><br><br>

<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><font color="#FFFFFF">As a result of current events, protests and freedom of speech have undoubteldy become one of the major discussions in our lives. Protests, criticisms and general intelligent opinions regarding our nation and its interaction with the world as well as domestic issues are important to our society. However, it seems that in our modern society many people simply do not understand the principles involved in our right to exercise free speech. </P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<i>Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the government for a redress of grievances.</i></P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
This entire rant is a consequence of a Columbia Professor, who obviously does not realize the implications of exercizing his right to run his mouth. For those of you fans who are less informed, Professor De Genova, an anthropology Professor speaking at a Anti-war Teach In held by other professors at our school said: "I wish for a million Mogadishus."  and also to ask for an Iraqi victory.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Mogadishu refers to the US involvement in Somalia in which 18 US Soldiers died. What De Genova seems to forget is that over 1000 Somalis were killed in the short conflict, and while the incident with US Soldiers being dragged around Mogadishu was horrifying, the thought of death tolls on both sides could or SHOULD be multiplied in this conflict is evidence of how clueless this man really is. In short his speech was found reprehensible by a large portion of the public (the story was run accross a slew of national media organizations) and even by members of the teach in. </P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Let's follow his logic for a moment, our involvement in the war in Iraq is regrettable as we are sending countless young Americans to risk death for a cause that is neither theirs nor necessarily righteous. In order to resolve this situation, he hopes for the death of a large proportion of these young soldiers, as if that would somehow equalize the morality of this war. </P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Another consequence of his remarks has been an outlash including death threats to him and indirectly the anthropology department. What was more shocking was that today as I walked accross campus, students were protesting to these threat by organizing a sit down on the steps. A sign read "We are students from Prof. De Genovas class and we usually have class at this time but because of death threats in reaction to his comments during the Teach In, he was forced to cancel class."  Who or what are you exactly protesting against here? What is this a demonstration of? Solidarity? That could be the case if half the students didn't gag themselves with American flags. What has the government done to Prof. De Genova? Nothing! The school? Nothing. </P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
WHERE IN FACT IN THIS ENTIRE INCIDENT HAS A PERSONS FIRST AMENDMENT RIGHT BEEN STEPPED ON? ACTUALLY, WHERE ALONG THE CHAIN OF EVENTS HAS ANYTHING REMOTELY REPRESENTED BY THE AMERICAN FLAG DONE ANYTHING OF PSYCHOLOGICAL, POLITICAL OR BODILY HARM TO THE PROFESSOR OR THOSE WHO AGREE WITH HIM? <b>NO WHERE!</b>(Unless you count the fact that some crazy people out there decided to send him death threats, which is akin to saying that we should protest america b/c there are some stupid and violent people in the nation.) As this is the case, take those flags out of your mouth and substitute it with your dirty rain trodden shoes.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>Truth is, the only real reactions from Columbia's community was an outcry of disgust with his comments. Even the school president found his remarks appalling. If this is what these students are demonstrating against, I would sincerely hope they realize that they are angry that President Bollinger and other faculty members are simply exercising their 1st amendment rights to tell De Genova what a flaming retard he was. The reality is that what comes out of your mouth has consequences. As a member of a community, an academic and intellectual community, you have the undocumented responsibility of realizing you do in some ways represent that community regardless of whether you want to or not.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
 The idea that what one says should not have any effect on how other people react is a sheer sign of mental incapacity. The whole reason we have freedom of speech is that speech is in and of itself a powerful motivator for education and a force for change/reaction. As a result, STUPID COMMENTS can often lead to NEGATIVE REACTIONS. It would be as naive to assume that I could run around Chinatown or Harlem and shout racial epithepts without having some fear of retaliation.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
In the end, De Genova keeps his job, there is no reaction from the government, but rightly so there is reaction from the local and national community. That is of course what the purpose of speech is! That students or this professor find it shocking that such reprehensible comments could agitate people to wish bodily harm when he wishes for the death of countless US and Iraqi lives, is an example of how students here at Columbia while academically gifted, may need some lessons in common sense.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Oh and in another note, he appears to have this historic problem with running his mouth to stir up controversy.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<i>"The heritage of the victims of the Holocaust belongs to the Palestinian people. The state of Israel has no legitimate claim to the heritage of the Holocaust. The heritage of the oppressed belongs to the oppressed--not the oppressor."</i></P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Yeah... real sweet there.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Oh and to De Genova, and his fans out there... Here's something I learned sometime during 1986 when I was reading See Spot Run in my kindergarten class. I believe many of you may have skipped that lecture.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
"Think before you speak."<BR>(It might just make the reaction you recieve a little less surprising to you)<BR></p></font></font>
