<br><b><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#4681BD" weight="bold">.:War:.</font></b><br>
<small><font size="1" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#0F7B66">Friday, March 21 2003</font></small><br><br>

<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><font color="#FFFFFF">Returned from a tropical paradise to the twenty-four seven coverage of conflict in Iraq. It's a strange contrast of two different worlds, New York and its all present security concerns with the warm blue relaxation of Hawaiian waters. </P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
In any case, we are once again at war. Many that I know feel discomforted, unsafe and worried about the current situation in our nation, fearful that we have subjected ourselves to inevitable retaliation and danger. As strange as it may be, I feel neither more insecure or nor worired than I was before I left. Perhaps it is a result of not really having any sort of substantial opinion on the matter of this conflict, either one side or another. </P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
At this point, I find myself uncomfortable with the war, simply in principle. Conflicts and death are sad in their conceptualization alone and it is here that I find certainty in my opinions on war. Battles are not something to be entered into lightly and our hope is of course always to find an alternative solution. War is sad because it is sometimes necessary.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
In another point, we hear constantly from opponents of the administration about this "unjust war." The concept of a JUST war to me seems to be one that we have entered into far too late. The only justification that appears universally appropriate for massive conflict is a preceding collosal loss of life and threat to global security. Our last "justified" conflicts were World War I and World War II in which our nations entry into battle was preceeded by millions of casualties and the destruction of entire nations. All Too little, All Too late. A generation devastated and years later ethnicities nearly wiped out. </P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Must we wait for horrifying consequences before action can be taken? We speak of diplomacy and yet we are constantly reminded of lessons we learned half a century ago, where diplomacy failed. No, we can never be certain that the terrible predictions we make today are assured to invoke themselves in the years to come. However, if given the chance to prevent the worst of our fears from occuring by fighting pre-emptive and currently unjustified battles now, should we? <BR></p></font></font>
<small><font size="1" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#0F7B66">
 [Karma: 0 (<A HREF="http://www.unityguild.com/cgi-bin/greymatter/gm-karma.cgi?vote=positive&amp;entry=00000025" onMouseOver="window.status='Cast a positive vote on this entry';return true" onMouseOut="window.status='';return true" class="bluelinksmall">+</A>/<A HREF="http://www.unityguild.com/cgi-bin/greymatter/gm-karma.cgi?vote=negative&amp;entry=00000025"  onMouseOver="window.status='Cast a negative vote on this entry';return true" onMouseOut="window.status='';return true" class="bluelinksmall">-</A>)] [<A HREF="http://www.unityguild.com/Fayvren/archives/00000025.htm#comments" onMouseOver="window.status='Add a comment to this entry';return true" onMouseOut="window.status='';return true" class="bluelinksmall">No Comments</A>]
</P></font></small><br>

<br><b><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#4681BD" weight="bold">.:Some thoughts:.</font></b><br>
<small><font size="1" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#0F7B66">Thursday, March 13 2003</font></small><br><br>

<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><font color="#FFFFFF">Elizabeth Smart was found today, when CNN.com sent me the breaking news e-mail I was to say shocked and surprised. It really is a wonderful thing. I mean, it's not often, in fact downright rare where missing people are found, especially young girls in this day and age.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
One thought that keeps resurfacing in my head about the entire incident is this man Ricci that they had suspected and eventually charged with burglary. At this point it seems sort of evident that he didn't take a major role in the kidnapping and yet for much of duration of the search the focus remained on him. In fact the media and much of the population wanted to believe that he was the guilty party. I've always wondered how many people the nation brands as killers and criminals are really innocent. I read an article earlier today about a man on death row that has been there for 22 years and the victim's family is absolutely positive he's the suspect. He could very well be, but what if he isn't? I suppose I am the defense attorney's witness, since I seem to always have a high degree of doubt in these matters. Victims of crimes are of course sad, but I find myself saddened by victims of society. Oh , and Ricci.... he died in prison of a brain hemmorage serving a sentence for burglary.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
In other news, I dunno why but I Feel really dazed and just downright confused lately. I dunno, I feel alone and yet Im not really alone or lonely at all. I dunno whats up.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
</p></font></font>
